WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.500
JOEL LEWIS: Hi.

00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:09.080
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:11.890
In lecture you discussed
the sum of the inverse

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:14.350
trigonometric functions as part
of your discussion of

00:00:14.350 --> 00:00:17.350
inverse functions in general,
and implicit differentiation.

00:00:17.350 --> 00:00:19.970
And I just wanted to talk about
one, briefly, that you

00:00:19.970 --> 00:00:23.760
didn't mention in lecture, as
far as I recall, which is the

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:24.620
inverse cosine.

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:27.890
So what I'm going to call
the arc cosine function.

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:32.460
So I just wanted to go briefly
through its graph and its

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:33.300
derivative.

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:37.110
So here I have the graph of the
curve, y equals cosine x.

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:39.850
So this is a, you know--

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:41.890
you should have seen this
before, I hope.

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:46.100
So it has at x equals 0 it
has its maximum value 1.

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:48.820
And then to the right
it goes down.

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:51.160
Its first 0 is at pi over 2.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:54.860
And then it has its trough
at x equals pie.

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:57.160
And then it goes
back up again.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:59.120
And, OK, and it's an even
function that looks the same

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:04.010
to the right and the
left of the y-axis.

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:06.970
And it's periodic with
period 2 pi.

00:01:06.970 --> 00:01:10.120
And it's also, you know, what
you get by shifting the sine

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:13.250
function, the graph of the
sine function to the

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:15.840
left by pi over 2.

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:18.100
So, OK, so this is y
equals cosine x.

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:22.680
So in order to graph y equals
arc cosine of x, we do what we

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:24.960
do for every inverse function,
which is we just take the

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:28.230
graph and we reflect it across
the line, y equals x.

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:30.630
So I've done that over here.

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:34.850
So this is what we get when
we reflect this curve--

00:01:34.850 --> 00:01:38.070
the y equals cosine x curve--
when we reflect it through

00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:41.170
that diagonal line,
y equals x.

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:43.060
So one thing you'll notice
about this is

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:44.310
that it's not a function.

00:01:44.310 --> 00:01:45.690
Right?

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:50.250
This curve is not the graph of
a function because every, all

00:01:50.250 --> 00:01:53.260
these humps on cosine x--

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.660
there are more humps
out here--

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:58.920
those horizontal lines cut
the humps in many points.

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:03.630
And when you reflect you get
vertical lines that cut this

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:05.400
curve in many points.

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:07.550
So it doesn't pass the
vertical line test.

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:10.460
So in order to get a function
out of this, what we have to

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:14.430
do is we just have to take a
chunk of this curve that does

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.000
pass the vertical line test.
And so there are many, many

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:17.820
ways we could do this.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:21.700
And we choose one basically
arbitrarily, meaning we could

00:02:21.700 --> 00:02:24.360
make a different choice, and
we could do all of our

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:27.140
trigonometry around some other
choice, but it's convenient to

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:30.120
just choose one and if everyone
agrees that that's

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.280
what that one is then we can
use it and it's nice.

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.700
We have a function and we can,
the other ones are all closely

00:02:37.700 --> 00:02:40.030
related to this one choice
that we can make.

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:45.140
So in particular here, I think
there's an easiest choice,

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:53.430
which is we take the curve, y
equals arc cosine x to be just

00:02:53.430 --> 00:03:00.800
this one piece of
the arc here.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.360
So this has maximum--

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:09.920
so it goes from x equals
minus 1 to x equals 1.

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:14.710
And when x is minus 1 we have
y is pi, and then when x

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:17.050
equals 1 y is 0.

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:25.550
So this is the, this curve is
the graph of the function, y

00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:27.030
equals arc cosine of x.

00:03:27.030 --> 00:03:30.870
And if you want-- so there's a
notation that mathematicians

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:34.650
use sometimes to show that
we're talking about the

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.690
particular arc cosine function
that has this as its domain

00:03:37.690 --> 00:03:38.860
and this as its range.

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:45.070
So we sometimes write
arc cosine and

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:46.320
it takes this domain--

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:51.090
the values between 1 and 1--

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:55.530
and it spits out values
between 0 and pi.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:59.680
So this is a sort of fancy
notation that mathematicians

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:04.070
use to say the arc cosine
function takes values in the

00:04:04.070 --> 00:04:06.430
interval minus 1, 1-- so
it takes values between

00:04:06.430 --> 00:04:08.240
negative 1 and 1--

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:11.650
and it spits out values in
the intervals 0, pi.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:15.330
So every value that it spits
out is between 0 and pi.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:20.910
OK, so if you graph the
function, so now this is a

00:04:20.910 --> 00:04:21.490
proper function.

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:22.270
Right?

00:04:22.270 --> 00:04:23.940
It's single-valued, it
passes the vertical

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:26.080
line test. So, OK.

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:29.970
And so that's the graph of
y equals arc cosine of x.

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:33.880
So the other thing that we did
in lecture, I think we talked

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.330
about arc sine and
we graphed it.

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:37.760
And we talked about arc
tan and we graphed it.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:39.330
And we also computed
their derivatives.

00:04:39.330 --> 00:04:42.185
So let's do that for the
arc cosine, as well.

00:04:45.470 --> 00:04:45.795
So what have we got?

00:04:45.795 --> 00:04:48.150
Well so, in order to compute
the derivative--

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:51.030
this function is defined as
an universe function--

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:53.640
so we do the same thing that we
did in lecture, which is we

00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:56.340
use this trick from implicit
differentiation.

00:04:56.340 --> 00:05:02.640
So in particular, we have that
if y is equal to arc cosine of

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:10.160
x then we can take the
cosine of both sides.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:12.940
And cosine of arc cosine, since
we've chosen it as an

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:16.420
inverse function, that
just gives us back x.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:21.830
So we get cosine of
y is equal to x.

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:23.150
And now we can differentiate.

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:27.130
So what we're after is the
derivative of arc cosine of x,

00:05:27.130 --> 00:05:28.980
so we're after dy dx.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:31.940
So we differentiate this through
with respect to x.

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:35.900
So on the right hand
side we just get 1.

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:38.560
And on the left hand side, well,
we have a chain rule

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:39.100
here, right?

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.150
Because we have cosine of y,
and y is a function of x.

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:51.980
So this is, so the derivative of
cosine is minus sine y, and

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:56.980
then we have to multiply
by the derivative of

00:05:56.980 --> 00:05:58.910
y, which is dy dx.

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:02.140
Now, dy dx is the thing we're
after, so we solve this

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:11.670
equation for dy dx and we get
dy dx is equal to minus 1

00:06:11.670 --> 00:06:16.170
divided by sine y.

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:18.130
OK, which is fine.

00:06:18.130 --> 00:06:21.360
This is a nice formula, but
what we'd really like,

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:24.410
ideally, is to express this
back in terms of x.

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:27.820
And so we can, well we can
substitute, right?

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.810
We have an expression
for y in terms of x.

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:33.420
So that's y is equal
to arc cosine of x.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:42.360
So this is equal to minus
1 divided by sine of

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:46.600
arc cosine of x.

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.760
Now, this looks really ugly.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:52.970
And here this is another place
where we could stop, but

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:55.490
actually it turns out that
because trigonometric

00:06:55.490 --> 00:07:00.980
functions are nicely behaved
we can make this nicer.

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:07.520
So I'm going to appeal here
to the case where x is

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:09.150
between 0 and 1.

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:12.660
So then x, so then
we have a right

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:14.200
triangle that we can draw.

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:16.780
And the other case you can do a
similar argument with a unit

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:20.250
circle, but I'll just
do this one case.

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:26.420
So if, OK so arc cosine of x.

00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:27.190
What does that mean?

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:29.870
That is the angle whose
cosine is x.

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:32.220
Right?

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:39.090
So if you draw a right triangle
and you make this

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:42.980
angle arc--

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:43.710
two c's--

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:47.210
arc cosine of x.

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:51.820
Well, that angle has cosine
equal to x so--

00:07:51.820 --> 00:07:54.840
and this is a right triangle--
so it's adjacent side over the

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:58.310
hypotenuse is equal to x, and
one easy way to get that

00:07:58.310 --> 00:08:01.630
arrangement of things is
say this side is x

00:08:01.630 --> 00:08:02.880
and the side is 1.

00:08:05.290 --> 00:08:05.580
So OK.

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:06.590
So what?

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:07.590
Why do I care?

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:11.030
Because I need sine
of that angle.

00:08:11.030 --> 00:08:14.130
So this is the angle arc cosine
of x, so sine of that

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:17.720
angle is the opposite side
over the hypotenuse.

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:18.790
And what's the opposite side?

00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:21.310
Well I can use the Pythagorean
theorem here, and the opposite

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:26.290
side is square root of
1 minus x squared.

00:08:26.290 --> 00:08:27.890
That's the length of
the opposite side.

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:34.720
So the sine of arc cosine of x
is square root of 1 minus x

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:36.870
squared divided by 1.

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:39.410
So sine of arc cosine of
x is just square root

00:08:39.410 --> 00:08:40.660
of 1 minus x squared.

00:08:40.660 --> 00:08:45.930
So we can write this in the
somewhat nicer form, minus 1

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:50.280
over the square root of
one minus x squared.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:56.160
So if you remember what the
derivative of arc sine of x

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:57.400
was, you'll notice that
this is a very

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:58.660
similar looking function.

00:08:58.660 --> 00:09:01.440
And this is just because cosine
and sine are very

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:04.030
similar looking functions.

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:08.800
So in fact, the graph of arc
cosine is just a reflection of

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:14.920
the graph of arc sine, and
that's why the derivatives are

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:17.540
so closely related
to each other.

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:17.990
So OK, so there you go.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:21.530
You've got the graph of arc
cosine up there and you've got

00:09:21.530 --> 00:09:25.010
the formula for its derivative,
so that sort of

00:09:25.010 --> 00:09:28.410
completes the tour of the
most important inverse

00:09:28.410 --> 00:09:30.060
trigonometric functions.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:31.990
So I think I'll end there.